 analysis of legal arguments and reviewing recent court actions, it refutes the policy perspectives that argue against reparations. Highlighting the human rights abuses inherent to and arising from slavery and ongoing racism, this book calls for governments to take responsibility for the impact of ongoing racialized injustice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxReparations. 0aAnti-racismzGreat Britain. 0aAnti-racismzUnited States. 0aBlack peoplezGreat BritainxSocial conditions. 0aBlack peoplezUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aBlacksxSocial conditionszGreat Britain. 0aBlacksxSocial conditionszUnited States. 0aReparations for historical injusticeszGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831111967560 cprintz978152921683740uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781529216851?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781529216851423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781529216851/original  a978-3-11-119675-6  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles